ProMED-ESP
<promed-esp@promedmail.org>

[The report above indicates that there is a continuation of the outbreak first reported in August 2011. As noted in the moderator comments in ProMED-mail archive no. 20110821.2548, in 1989, there was an outbreak of a severe febrile illness in Portuguesa state, mainly among male and female rural inhabitants of all ages in the southern part of the state, characterized by fever, headache, myalgia, sore throat, weakness, anorexia, nausea, vomiting, and occasionally convulsions. Since then, there have been sporadic cases, with a 40 percent case fatality rate.

The rodent reservoirs are the cotton rat _Sigmodon alstoni_ and the cane mouse _Zygodontomys brevicauda_. Guanarito virus is an arenavirus related to 2 other South American arenaviruses: Machupo virus (Bolivian hemorrhagic fever) and Junin virus (Argentinean hemorrhagic fever).

An image of _Sigmodon alstoni_ can be accessed at http://monde.des.mammiferes.free.fr/Placentaires/Rodentia/Cricetidae/Sigmodon%20hispidus.jpg
and of _Zygodontomys brevicauda_ at http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/site/resources/Heideman_Paul/Zygod_brevicauda/medium.jpg.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map showing the location of Portuguesa state can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/1ZVY. - Mod.TY]
